					<head>Pentateuch</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/n79066420" rend="visible">
						<summary>Pentateuch accompanied by masorah magna and masorah parva.</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he">Hebrew</textLang>
						<msItem n="0" rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/n79066420">
							<locus from="1r" to="196v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Torah</title>
							<title xml:lang="he">תורה</title>
							<textLang mainLang="he">Hebrew</textLang>
							<decoNote type="marginal">Masorah in the margin written in micrographic form. 18 full-page panels of micrographical design.<locus from="2v-7r" to="192r-196r">
									<g/>
								</locus>
							</decoNote>
							<filiation> Some micrographicial motifs are similar to Harley MS 5774, <ref target="Margoliouth_1965" type="number">121</ref>
							</filiation>
							<note>
								<p>See <ref target="Pettigrew_1827" type="page">XVI-XVII</ref>. </p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="2r" to="8v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Masoretic lists</title>
							<note>
								<p>Chronology of biblical books from Genesis to Kings.</p>
								<p>List of the authors of the biblical books.</p>
								<p>Number of verses in the Bible and its parts.</p>
								<p>Number of letters in the Torah.</p>
								<p>Chronology of the biblical period.</p>
								<p>Alphabetical list of the words that occur twice in the Bible but with different meaning.</p>
								<p>List of the verses in which all the letters of the alphabet occur.</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="8v" to="53r"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Genesis</title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="53r" to="92v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Exodus</title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="92v" to="119v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Leviticus</title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="119v" to="157v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Numbers</title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="157v" to="192v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Deuteronomy</title>
							<note>Missing chapter 12:17 (in part) to the end.</note>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="192v" to="196v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Masoretic lists.</title>
							<note>
								<p>List of the words that are read but not written.</p>
								<p>List of the passages in which certain words are marked with dots.</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of late 14th or early 15th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<support>Parchment codex.</support>
								<extent rend="visible">196 folios<dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>290</height>
										<width>215</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>180</height>
										<width>135</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>196 folios (+ 1 unfoliated parchment flyleaf at the beginning and at the end).</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>25 quires: i6, ii-xxiv8, xxv5, numbered at the beginning of each quire.</p>
								</collation>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="2" ruledLines="25" writtenLines="25">
									<p>Uniform layout. </p>
									<p>Masorah magna often written in the form of figures, animals and patterns; otherwise it occupies three lines in the upper margin and two in the lower margin.</p>
									<p>Round the margins of folios 2v-7r and 192r-196r there is an unpunctuated text of parts of Psalms in large square characters</p>
									<p>Ruling with hard point on the hair-side of folios, hardly visible.</p>
									<p>The beginning of the weekly section is marked by פרש' in the margin. The chapters and subdivisions having been noted by means of Hebrew letters in later writing.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc>
							<summary>Sefardi square script of late 14th or early 15th century, with punctuation.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="major"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="owner">Petri Arrivabeni</name>: inscribed with his name: ‘Io petri Arriuabeni’, undated (folio 1r). </p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="owner">David Yitsḥaḳ Karmi</name>: inscribed with his name in an owner’s inscription, undated (folio 2r). </p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="owner">Yitsḥaḳ Kohen ben [ .. .. ] Yoshu῾a Kohen</name>: inscribed with his name in an owner’s inscription (folio 2r). </p>
							<p>Illegible Latin inscription (folio 195v). </p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="censor">Giovanni Domenico Carretto</name>, Italian censor (active 1600-1624): inscribed with his name, 1612 (folio 196r ); see <ref target="Popper_1969" type="page">100-101</ref>1. </p>
							<p>Italian inscription: ‘Pentateuco Ebraico ossia li cinque libri di Moise’ (folio 196v). </p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p>Post-1600. Crimson velvet binding.</p>
								<p>Boxed.</p>
								<p>Spine: &apos;Pentateuchus Hebraice. M.S. in Membrana. Mus. Brit. Jure Emptionis. 15,306. Plut.&apos;</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
